✨Hot Cocoa Spoons✨
Sure you can buy them but they’re so easy AND FUN to make. An easy no-bake gift for when you want to give something homemade but don’t have time or feel like baking. 
This is also a great project to do with kids, and would be a fun homemade gift for them to give teachers and classmates. What’s also great about making instead of buying them is you can use real spoons. The ones I used are from Target but you can scout antique shops for some vintage spoons to make them extra special. 
I topped mine with crushed peppermint and marshmallows. Toffee bits, white chocolate chips and peanut butter chips would all be yummy, too. 

📝All you need are chocolate melts or chips (I used @ghirardelli milk chocolate wafers), toppings, spoons, muffins tins (mini, regular size or both), and silicon liners or wax coated paper liners so the chocolate spoons lift out easily. Don’t forget pretty bags & ribbon to package them. 
✨✨✨
Happy First day of December! May the hot cocoa and holiday cheer be plentiful this next month!🎄✨

✨today’s Christmas cookie spotlight is one I’m perhaps most known for, Italian Rainbow Cookies. These have been a favorite since my childhood in Brooklyn, and an Italian-American recipe with no real roots in Italy that I know of but that doesn’t detract from their meaning and beloved status here. They’re an expensive cookie to buy because of the almond paste needed, and I find also a hard cookie to get a really great one because many bakeries now use cheap almond paste products. 
I recommend making the almond paste from scratch which is quite easy, or seeking out a good quality one. Patience is key since the cookie is made in stages. First you bake the layers, then once cooled, you assemble them and have to wait overnight (or the equivalent) for them to set. Once the layers are snug together, they get coated in chocolate which then needs another good few hours to set before cutting. 
People who don’t normally like Rainbow Cookies always tell me mine are the first they’ve ever liked, and I do swear it’s the almond paste that makes all the difference. 
Christmas Eve is one week from today, Hanukkah starts on Sunday, AND at 1pm-ish today my 10 day break from work starts. Now all I need is the weather to cooperate so I can pick my Bella boo up from college tomorrow, and it’s going to be full on holiday cheer from there. 
Much love to all of you out there. Thanks for being such a kind, caring group of humans. —xo, j.

✨today’s Christmas cookie highlight is a special duo made for a sweet friend and her husband who are #glutenfree and #dairyfree. When I laid out all the cookies to pack tins earlier this week all I saw were the two missing treats I didn’t get to make (zimsterne & chocolate truffles), and had to give myself a stern talking about why I do this. 
It’s a true labor of love, fit into early mornings, late nights, and weekends. I don’t do it because I have to, I do it because I want to. It keeps me grounded the month of December. It is a tradition that weaves together the parts of my life that no longer exist in this living world. 
It nourishes my soul, and is the the language I use to express how thankful I am to the people who’ve positively impacted my life every year. To everyone who received a tin, or any baked treat, this year: thank you for being you.

✨I started keeping a vegetable scrap bag in the freezer about 12 years ago. Once it’s filled, that means it’s time for a pot of homemade veggie broth with all the rescued bits and bobs. In the main bag I keep trimming, peelings and the ends/tops of celery, carrots, leeks, onions (skins, too!), herb stems, garlic, and all the other main components you’d use for a basic stock. 

In separate bags I keeps things like corn cobs which add a subtle sweet note to stocks. I keep yet one other bag for ginger and scallions when I want to draw in some of those flavors, too, but always keep them separate so I can make the base stock and keep the flavor more universal. 

The stock tastes slightly different every time depending on what’s in the bag. This one was heavy on parsley stems, celery and onion bits, so I’m adding corn cobs from last summer. It’ll be a sweet, herbaceous stock. I could throw in some sundried tomatoes for some more depth of flavor. I just might go dig them out of the pantry now!

✨I’ve been leaning into my air fryer more and more, realizing it’s the perfect tool when cooking for one or two, or in small batches. A couple of weeks ago, I roasted a whole head of cauliflower and it was perfection. My air-fryer is on the smaller side & this was a petite head, weighing about 24 ounces. I went with a few drizzles of olive oil, salt & pepper but was almost tempted to use the rosey harissa from @nyshuk…next time. I’m also going to try a version basted with BBQ sauce during the last few minutes of cooking. Imagine teriyaki sauce would be great, too…limitless possibilities. 

For dinner that night I made grain bowls with quinoa, hummus, baby spinach, crispy chickpeas and chunks of this roasted cauliflower. It was even teenager approved (the cauliflower, not the grain bowls!). 

Cooking method: first do a fit test for your cauliflower head before preheating your air-fryer to 375°F. Once preheated, season cauliflower as desired, then roast until a paring knife inserted at the base easily pierces the cauliflower, 35 to 40 minutes but remember cook times vary depending on size of cauliflower and air-fryer. Enjoy! 🍽️

Last night’s Passover Seder, a little belated due to college schedules. The days feel long when your children are little, even more so for single parents. Then one day you wake up and realize just how short the years themselves were. 

While cooking dinner yesterday, Michael was ever-present on my mind, as were his grandparents. They passed away long before I met Michael but were his guiding forces, and a big reason I’m steadfast in my commitment to ensure their great grandchildren feel connected to their Jewish heritage. 

Michael was being trained in private for his Bar Mitzvah, and when his catholic father found out, he was furious, and wouldn’t talk to Michael so he dropped out of the training, and that set him on a path of wandering and wondering his whole life. 

Michael was a deeply thoughtful person, and strongly felt all religion was essentially fear mongering and mind control, I think a result of his experiences at home. I agree any religion can be distorted for those purposes, especially having been raised Catholic but then deciding to leave the church when I was 12 years old for those very reasons. 

Once we had children, though, something started to spark in Mikey, a curiosity that I genuinely believe would’ve led our little family to the same path I’m now on with our children. I often joked we had to raise them with something just so they’d have something to reject as we both did. In reality, their Jewish heritage is the string that tethers us to the person we miss most in this world. 

I don’t know what happens before we’re born, or after we die. What I do know is that what we do with our time on this earth creates ripples that reach far beyond our human existence.

✨Recently found myself with a ridiculous number of whole heads of garlic, so decided to roast a bunch of them in my air fryer. Super easy and I find roasted garlic adds a more delicate, pleasant flavor to anything you’d normally add garlic to, especially hummus and falafel, but also lovely for salad dressings. 
Once cooled, I pop them from the papery peels, mash and add to a jar, then cover it with olive oil. Stored in the fridge, it lasts quite long. You can even smash some on a baguette and top with goat cheese for an easy appetizer (maybe a sprinkling of chives, too), or smash onto bread and sprinkle on some pecorino cheese & chopped parsley for garlic bread. 
Of course it’s also perfect simply tossed with pasta and a few drizzles of olive oil. 
To make this yourself, follow the video and you’ll see I added salt, pepper and olive oil. No measurements needed. I cooked mine at 375F for about 20 minutes, but trust your nose here and check as soon as the house fills with a toasty, nutty scent of roasting garlic.
.

🧅✨ While cooking pot of chickpeas recently, I only needed half an onion, and decided to show you the best way to save the other half while also getting a jump on your next meal. 
Just chop the other half, store it in a container in the freezer (I like to label the front of containers instead of the top for easier reference when their stacked), then use as needed. No thawing necessary; you can use it straight from the freezer.
I also keep a bag in the freezer to save vegetable trimmings. Things like the roots of onions, onions skin, bits and bobs from herbs, celery, and even carrot peelings go into the bag. Once it’s filled, just add the ingredients to a pot, cover with water, add some salt and pepper, then bring it to a boil, and let it simmer to make an easy homemade vegetable broth from all of your veggie scraps.

✨Homemade Vanilla Extract✨
Consider this a reminder to get your batch started so it’ll be ready to use for all your holiday baking needs. I know, I know, September is barely done but my December baking prep work starts now. What can I say? It’s little details like homemade extracts, candied fruits, etc. that add the extra special touches. 

To make this extract, you’ll need vanilla beans & vodka. That’s it! Buy good quality beans but cheap vodka. Don’t waste your money on the fancy drinking stuff. You’ll need 3 beans for every cup of vodka. 

Use a sharp paring knife to split the beans open to expose the tiny seeds inside. You can then add the beans to a jar and cover with vodka, or add the beans directly to the bottle of vodka. Give it a good shake to release the seeds from the pod, and store it in a cool, dark place, shaking occasionally, until it’s a dark amber color, about 2 months.

The final extract can be stored in the bottle with the seeds,  and used as needed, or transfer it into smaller jars. Use it in all of your favorite baking recipes, or give it as gifts for any occasion.

✨Recipe of the day is no recipe required. These crispy chickpeas can be made in the oven, as I used to, but it’s one more reason my air fryer has become my most used kitchen appliance. 

Tip tinned chickpeas into a strainer, rinse & drain, then transfer to a kitchen to rub off the skins. They won’t all come off, you can pop them off with your finger if you want but I was feeling a little lazy the day I filmed this. 

Toss the chick peas in a bowl with a little bit of olive oil, season with salt & pepper, a dash of tamari or coconut amino acids & sprig of rosemary. You can add other flavors, like @nyshuk  rosey harissa or shawarma spice, or just some smoked paprika, if you want. 

Transfer the coated chickpeas to an air fryer preheated to 400°F, and cook, shaking the basket occasionally, until crisp & browned. Time varies with air fryers. Get to know yours…mine took about 15 minutes. 

OVEN DIRECTIONS: prepare chickpeas as noted above. Spread them onto a rimmed baking sheet & roast at 425°F until crisp and browned, shaking the pan occasionally, for 25 to 30 minutes.

14 years ago Michael gifted me this cookbook for our 5th wedding anniversary. It is one of my most cherished possessions, marrying both of our backgrounds. I read it as one would a book, immersing myself in Edda Servi Machlin’s story of growing up Jewish in Pitigiliano. 

In the late 1850s,  there were 400+ Jews in Pitigliano. The population dipped to 70 in the early 1930s, many moved to other parts of Tuscany while others converted to Christianity. 

During WWII more Italian Jews moved away, some were deported and the rest hid in the hills with families that took them in. By time the war was over, only 30 Jews returned to Pitigliano. Today that number can be counted on one hand. 

The number of wedding anniversaries we’ve spent apart far surpasses how many we celebrated together. Soon the years he’s been gone will be longer than the years we were alive together. The constant…the glue that keeps us tethered are my memories and our children. His Jewish heritage is their Jewish heritage. This is what I consider to be one of my biggest responsibilities as the keeper of his story. 

The last photo here is of Michael’s British born Jewish grandparents, Irving & Rose Ross. I love them even though I never met them. I honor their memories by making sure their grandchildren know their story. 

Happy anniversary, Mikey. I love you always.

✨After years of watching @amybethcupp bake muffins, I finally gave her master recipe a try. Amy tweaks with the seasons, adding berries in the summer, zucchini other times of the year, and even shared notes for using pumpkin. 
This was my first time making them but I can see how this is an incredibly adaptable recipe. I made some tweaks myself, so this is the recipe version of the old game of telephone. I halved the recipe, and still got a generous 16 muffins which could’ve been whittled down to a dozen. I was cautious in filling the muffin cups since I didn’t know how much they would rise. 
I added some Lebkuchengewürz (German gingerbread spice) and a little bit of brown sugar in addition to the honey, as well as using Amy’s tip for subbing in canned pumpkin. Sprinkled some pumpkin seeds & coarse sugar on top for texture.
The real game changer, though, and this is something to consider for many baked goods—let your mixed batter rest a bit, up to 20 minutes before baking. It helps the flour absorb the wet ingredients and produced a noticeable difference in the texture and rise of the second tray that baked.

First 10,000 steps & first sunset of 2024.
There were lots of questions & interest in my last post about tracking macros, and how I do it. I want to preface I’m not an expert here—learning as I go. What I am an expert in, though, is my own body, having lived in it for 50 years. What worked in my 20s, 30s, and even early 40s just stopped working. 
Rather than talk about everything I did that didn’t work, I’m going to share what did: tracking my macros using the MacrosFirst app, switching from using my step elliptical for cardio and focusing on strength training + commitment to hitting 8K - 10K steps a day, and SLEEP.

The only way these strategies work is a daily commitment to prioritizing them. Some days go along easy peasy, and others are a constant negotiation of reprioritizing my day to ensure I’m eating well and getting in my steps. 

What tracking macros taught me is that it’s not enough to just count calories. Like everything else in life, it’s about the calories being in balance—my balance after entering my weight loss goal into MacrosFirst based on my current height, weight, age, and level of activity is my calories composition should be roughly 29% protein, 41% carbs & 30% fat based on 1506 daily calories (remember I’m in a calorie deficit right now for weight loss).

I’m sharing these numbers to show that carbs are a part of my life. The main issue for me was the vegetarian sources of protein I used to lean into are very high in carbs and not high enough in protein per serving. I have no ethical issues eating meat or seafood, so bringing those foods back into my diet was fine. I’m not advocating for us to all double down on animal protein. I’m just being realistic that this model will be more challenging if you’re trying to eat a strictly vegetarian or vegan diet.

I still eat beans but now will opt to omit the rice from a burrito bowl, or swap in cauliflower rice. If I want to eat rice it’s better for me paired with a protein like shrimp or chicken breast. (continued in comments)

Numbers don’t lie but they also don’t tell the whole story. There've been many times in my life where I’ve felt good in my body, could feel the changes happening, only to have my perception shattered once I stepped on the scale. In my 20s, I joked this was a shifting of the continental plates in my body—same mass, just in different places.

What I now understand is that numbers on a scale are only part of the story when it comes to how your body is affected by exercise. The feeling that my body is different in a good way is because it is. I can feel it in the way my pants fall on my hips. I can see it in how my arms look. That’s because fat is converting to muscle. The numbers look the same on the scale but they’re distributed differently on my body. This is why some people track inches instead of pounds, and in some cases both. 

I’ve had two moments during the last seven weeks when I felt excited to weigh myself only to end giving myself a pep talk and reminder of how my clothes feel differently—that I feel good being in my body. I don’t know if the feeling will ever go away when the scale doesn’t read supposed success even though I know better now, but I don't feel discouraged, and that’s progress. I also still prefer not to measure myself to track inches lost.

There’s so many mixed messages during January. We go from an excess of gluttony to an excess of deprivation at the stroke of midnight. Don’t let it discourage you. Trust your instincts. 

What I’ve learned, finally, is to watch a new workout before setting out to do it. Do you have the equipment needed to get started? Can you reasonably do the exercises being shown, and if not, what can you do to modify it to make it work for you? I personally can’t do lunges, and landed in physical therapy years ago due to a trainer not listening to what I was telling him about my body. 

I’ve no idea what the future holds but I know what I hope to feel like physically and mentally. Right now—this is the moment that decides what some of the future will look like.
